ian, post- Freudian, Lacanian, and post-structuralist schools, Alcorn investigates the power of the text that underlies the reader response approach to literature in a strikingly new way. He shows how the production of literary texts begins and ends with narcissistic self-love, and also shows how the reader's interest in these texts is directed by libidinal investment.Psychoanalysts, psychologists, and lovers of literature will enjoy Alcorn's diverse and far-reaching insights into classic and contemporary writers and thinkers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aNarcissism in literature. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 4aThis. 4abook. 4achange. 4acompels. 4aconcepts. 4aeffect. 4aexplain. 4ainvestment. 4alibidinal. 4anarcissism. 4apsychoanalytic. 4arhetoric. 4auses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814707517423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814707517.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK